<main>

  <div class="abstract">
    <div class="section-label">Abstract</div>
    <p>Orbital AI compute demands radiation-hard substrates beyond silicon's limits. Diamond excels with a 5.5 eV bandgap for SEU resistance, 2,000 W/mK thermal conductivity, and UV–IR transparency for photonics. This paper proposes a closed-loop orbital chain—ureilite asteroid carbon via pyrolysis to solar-powered CVD—structured in three phases (2026–2050) converging ISRU, solar manufacturing, and diamond electronics.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- 1. INTRODUCTION -->

  <section>
    <div class="section-label">01</div>
    <h2>Substrate Imperative</h2>
    <p>Silicon chips launched from Earth inherit terrestrial fab limits, vulnerable to cosmic ray single-event upsets (SEUs) that flip bits despite hardening overhead. Diamond's 5.5 eV bandgap inherently resists such upsets—versus silicon's 1.1 eV. Ureilites offer orbital carbon at 2–4 wt%, microgravity CVD has 1995 precedent, and solar flux supplies energy. Integration unlocks the pathway; the constituent technologies exist.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- 2. DIAMOND -->

  <section>
    <div class="section-label">02</div>
    <h2>Diamond Superiority</h2>

```
<h3>2.1 — Radiation Resilience</h3>
<p>SEU cross-section drops with bandgap; diamond ignores fluxes that corrupt silicon. Grain boundaries pose residual risks, addressable via defect engineering. Radiation-hard silicon sacrifices 30–50% die area to redundancy—diamond reclaims it at the material level.</p>

<h3>2.2 — Thermal Edge</h3>
<p>Diamond conducts heat at ~2,000 W/mK versus silicon's ~150 W/mK—a 13× advantage critical in vacuum without convective cooling. GaN-on-diamond prototypes demonstrate high-power viability at the substrate, not the package.</p>

<h3>2.3 — Photonic Fit</h3>
<p>Full-spectrum UV–IR transparency enables hybrid electro-photonic compute, directly suited to volumetric AI accelerator architectures.</p>
```

  </section>

  <!-- 3. FEEDSTOCK -->

  <section>
    <div class="section-label">03</div>
    <h2>Orbital Feedstock</h2>

```
<h3>3.1 — Ureilite Composition</h3>
<p>Ureilite asteroids from disrupted bodies contain graphite-dominant carbon suitable as CVD feedstock, alongside lonsdaleite and minor diamond. Silicate and metal contaminants are chemically separable.</p>

<div class="table-wrap">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Property</th>
        <th>Value / Note</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Carbon content</td><td>2–4 wt%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dominant phase</td><td>Graphite — processable CVD feedstock</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Diamond fraction</td><td>≤1% of carbon</td></tr>
      <tr><td>CVD precursors</td><td>CH₄ / H₂ via pyrolysis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Contaminants</td><td>Silicates, Fe, S — separable</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Precedents</td><td>Wake Shield CVD (1995); MOXIE ISRU (2021)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<h3>3.2 — Pyrolysis Route</h3>
<p>H₂-assisted thermal cracking mirrors established ISRU propellant chemistry. The primary challenge is purification to electronics-grade standard (&lt;1 ppm N)—the physics is not novel.</p>
```

  </section>

  <!-- 4. SOLAR -->

  <section>
    <div class="section-label">04</div>
    <h2>Solar Furnace Energy</h2>
    <p>Orbital irradiance of 1,366 W/m² via 500 m² deployable optics meets CVD's kilowatt-scale demand, yielding an estimated ~2 kg diamond per year at zero fuel cost. This inverts terrestrial energy economics. Deployable concentrator technology is maturing now.</p>
  </section>

